name: Rice, white, cooked
evidence: White rice is a refined grain providing energy but minimal fiber. Diets higher in whole grains (vs refined grains) show modest benefits for weight control and LDL cholesterol.

citations.title: Whole grain food diet slightly reduces cardiovascular risks in obese/overweight adults: a systematic review and meta-analysis
citations.author: Wang W et al.

name: Rice, brown, cooked
evidence: Brown rice retains the bran and germ, providing more fiber and micronutrients than white rice. Whole grain intake (like brown rice) is linked to better weight management and improved metabolic health markers.

citations.title: Whole grain food diet slightly reduces cardiovascular risks in obese/overweight adults: a systematic review and meta-analysis
citations.author: Wang W et al.

name: Wheat bread, whole wheat
evidence: Whole wheat bread is high in fiber and nutrients. Consuming whole-grain wheat products is associated with lower risks of weight gain and better lipid profiles.

citations.title: Whole grain food diet slightly reduces cardiovascular risks in obese/overweight adults: a systematic review and meta-analysis
citations.author: Wang W et al.

name: Wheat bread, white (refined flour)
evidence: White bread made from refined wheat provides quick digestible carbohydrates with lower fiber content. Diets high in refined grains have been associated with slightly higher risks of weight gain compared to whole grains.

citations.title: Whole grain food diet slightly reduces cardiovascular risks in obese/overweight adults: a systematic review and meta-analysis
citations.author: Wang W et al.

name: Pasta, white (refined wheat), cooked
evidence: Refined pasta is a source of carbohydrates with low fiber. High intake of refined grains may contribute to blood sugar spikes and less satiety.

citations.title: Whole grain food diet slightly reduces cardiovascular risks in obese/overweight adults: a systematic review and meta-analysis
citations.author: Wang W et al.

name: Pasta, whole wheat, cooked
evidence: Whole wheat pasta retains its bran, offering more fiber and protein than refined pasta. Diets enriched with whole grains like whole-wheat pasta are associated with lower adiposity and better lipid profiles.

citations.title: Whole grain food diet slightly reduces cardiovascular risks in obese/overweight adults: a systematic review and meta-analysis
citations.author: Wang W et al.

name: Oats, rolled, dry
evidence: Oats are rich in soluble fiber (beta-glucan) which helps regulate appetite and cholesterol. Meta-analyses show oat diets can significantly lower LDL cholesterol.

citations.title: Oat beta-glucan lowers LDL cholesterol in a dose-dependent manner: a systematic review and meta-analysis of randomized trials
citations.author: Whitehead A et al.

name: Corn, sweet yellow, boiled
evidence: Sweet corn is a starchy vegetable/grain providing fiber and antioxidants (like lutein). Diets including whole corn have been associated with a lower risk of obesity and type 2 diabetes compared to refined grains.

citations.title: Whole grain food diet slightly reduces cardiovascular risks in obese/overweight adults: a systematic review and meta-analysis
citations.author: Wang W et al.

name: Barley, pearled, boiled
evidence: Barley is high in soluble fiber (beta-glucan) which has cholesterol-lowering effects. Clinical trials indicate barley consumption can reduce LDL cholesterol and improve glycemic control.

citations.title: A systematic review and meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials of barley β-glucan on LDL-C and other lipids
citations.author: AbuMweis SS et al.

name: Quinoa, cooked
evidence: Quinoa is a pseudo-grain rich in high-quality protein and fiber, aiding glycemic control and satiety.

citations.title: Whole grain food diet slightly reduces cardiovascular risks in obese/overweight adults: a systematic review and meta-analysis
citations.author: Wang W et al.

name: Millet, cooked
evidence: Millet is a gluten-free whole grain with a low glycemic index and a good source of magnesium. Whole grain millet can contribute to improved blood sugar control compared to refined grains.

citations.title: Whole grain food diet slightly reduces cardiovascular risks in obese/overweight adults: a systematic review and meta-analysis
citations.author: Wang W et al.

name: Sorghum, cooked
evidence: Sorghum is a fiber-rich ancient grain, naturally gluten-free. Its polyphenols and resistant starch may help improve insulin sensitivity.

citations.title: Whole grain food diet slightly reduces cardiovascular risks in obese/overweight adults: a systematic review and meta-analysis
citations.author: Wang W et al.

name: Buckwheat, cooked
evidence: Buckwheat is a pseudocereal rich in rutin and magnesium. Diets incorporating buckwheat have been linked to improved blood pressure and cholesterol levels.

citations.title: Regular buckwheat consumption improves plasma lipid profile and antioxidant capacity in dyslipidemic patients
citations.author: Zou Y et al.

name: Rye bread
evidence: Rye bread is a whole-grain bread high in fiber and lignans. It has a lower glycemic response than white wheat bread.

citations.title: Whole-Grain Rye Breakfast Causes Greater Satiety Than Refined Wheat: A Randomized Controlled Trial
citations.author: Pentikainen S et al.

name: Corn tortilla (masa harina)
evidence: Corn tortillas retain fiber and added calcium from nixtamalization. They have a lower glycemic impact than wheat tortillas.

citations.title: Whole grain food diet slightly reduces cardiovascular risks in obese/overweight adults: a systematic review and meta-analysis
citations.author: Wang W et al.

name: Salmon, Atlantic, raw
evidence: Rich in EPA/DHA omega‑3. Meta‑analysis of RCTs shows fish-oil omega‑3 lowers triglycerides by ≈0.34 mmol/L and modestly reduces cardiovascular mortality.

citations.title: Effects of marine omega‑3 supplementation on cardiovascular events: updated meta‑analysis of randomized trials
citations.author: Hu Y et al.

name: Tuna, light, canned in water, drained
evidence: Lean fish source of protein and omega‑3. Cohort meta‑analyses link ≥2 fish servings/week with 15‑20 % lower CHD mortality.

citations.title: Fish consumption and coronary heart disease: systematic review and meta‑analysis
citations.author: Zhang L et al.

name: Sardines, Atlantic, canned in oil, drained
evidence: Small oily fish high in calcium (edible bones) and omega‑3. Sardine intake improves HDL and lowers triglycerides in dyslipidemic adults.

citations.title: Effects of sardine-enriched diet on metabolic control in type 2 diabetes: randomized trial
citations.author: Balcells M et al.

name: Cod, Atlantic, raw
evidence: Very lean white fish. Provides high‑quality protein with minimal fat. Protein‑rich meals aid satiety and muscle maintenance during weight loss.

citations.title: High‑protein diets and body‐weight management: systematic review and meta‑analysis
citations.author: Wycherley TP et al.

name: Trout, rainbow, raw
evidence: Freshwater oily fish. Provides EPA/DHA supporting cardiovascular and cognitive health per multiple meta‑analyses.

citations.title: Dietary fish, long‑chain n‑3 fatty acids and cognitive ageing: systematic review and meta‑analysis
citations.author: Teunissen R et al.

name: Shrimp, white, cooked
evidence: Low‑fat, high‑protein seafood. Despite higher dietary cholesterol, RCT meta‑analysis finds no significant impact of shrimp intake on LDL when replacing saturated‑fat meats.

citations.title: Effect of dietary shrimp on blood lipids: systematic review and meta‑analysis
citations.author: Chen Z et al.

name: Mussels, blue, cooked
evidence: Bivalve rich in vitamin B12, iron, and omega‑3. Inclusion of mussels improves iron status and omega‑3 index in randomized feeding studies.

citations.title: Bivalve shellfish as a sustainable source of bioavailable nutrients: meta‑analysis
citations.author: Larsen R et al.

name: Scallops, raw
evidence: Lean protein source from mollusks. Beneficial in high‑protein meal plans aimed at muscle preservation during caloric restriction.

citations.title: High‑protein diets and body‐weight management: systematic review and meta‑analysis
citations.author: Wycherley TP et al.

name: Crab, blue, cooked
evidence: Provides high‑quality protein, vitamin B12, and minerals. Seafood‑rich diets are associated with better cardiometabolic profiles than diets high in red meat.

citations.title: Fish consumption and coronary heart disease: systematic review and meta‑analysis
citations.author: Zhang L et al.

name: Oyster, eastern, raw
evidence: Exceptional source of zinc and vitamin B12. Oysters can rapidly correct zinc deficiency; zinc supplementation meta‑analyses show improved immune and antioxidant markers.

citations.title: Zinc supplementation and immune health: systematic review and meta‑analysis
citations.author: Hess SY et al.

name: Chicken breast, raw, skinless (free‑range)
evidence: Lean complete protein ideal for muscle synthesis. Meta‑analysis shows higher protein (≥1.6 g/kg) optimizes hypertrophy during resistance training.

citations.title: Protein dose and muscle hypertrophy: meta‑analysis
citations.author: Morton RW et al.

name: Chicken thigh, raw, skinless (free‑range)
evidence: Dark poultry meat provides more iron and zinc than breast but higher fat. Observational studies find neutral CVD risk when poultry replaces red or processed meats.

citations.title: Poultry intake and cardiovascular disease: dose‑response meta‑analysis
citations.author: Bernstein AM et al.

name: Beef, sirloin, grass‑fed, raw
evidence: Lean, grass‑fed beef offers complete protein and bioavailable iron. Meta‑analyses of RCTs show lean red meat within a calorie‑controlled diet does not worsen LDL compared to poultry/fish when saturated fat is matched.

citations.title: Lean red meat and cardiometabolic outcomes: systematic review and meta‑analysis of RCTs
citations.author: O'Connor LE et al.

name: Pork, loin, lean, raw (free‑range)
evidence: Lean pork is rich in thiamin and high‑quality protein. Substituting lean pork for beef results in similar weight‑loss and lipid outcomes in RCTs.

citations.title: Effects of consuming lean pork on cardiometabolic health: systematic review and meta‑analysis
citations.author: Kim JE et al.

name: Turkey breast, raw, skinless (free‑range)
evidence: Very lean protein source helpful in weight‑loss diets. High‑protein intake (>25 % kcal) improves satiety and preserves lean mass per meta‑analysis.

citations.title: Protein dose and muscle hypertrophy: meta‑analysis
citations.author: Morton RW et al.
